# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: great-ormond-street-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The opening ceremony of the 2012 Summer Olympics took place on the evening of Friday 27 July 2012 in the Olympic Stadium, London, during which the Games were formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As mandated by the Olympic Charter, the proceedings combined the ceremonial opening of this international sporting event (including welcoming speeches, hoisting of the flags and the parade of athletes) with an artistic spectacle to showcase the host nation's culture.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The spectacle was entitled ***Isles of Wonder*** and directed by the Academy Award-winning British film director Danny Boyle, with Paulette Randall as associate director.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Prior to London 2012, there had been considerable apprehension about Britain's ability to stage an opening ceremony that could reach the standard set at the Beijing Summer Games of 2008.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 2008 ceremony had been noted for its scale, extravagance and expense, hailed as the "greatest ever", and had cost £65m.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In contrast, London spent an estimated £27m (out of £80m budgeted for its four ceremonies), which was nevertheless about twice the original budget.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Nonetheless, the London opening ceremony was immediately seen as a tremendous success, widely praised as a "masterpiece" and "a love letter to Britain".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony began at 21:00 BST and lasted almost four hours.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was watched by an estimated worldwide television audience of 900 million, falling short of the IOC's 1.5 billion viewership estimate for the 2008 ceremony, but becoming the most viewed in the UK and US.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The content had largely been kept secret before the performance, despite involving thousands of volunteers and two public rehearsals.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The principal sections of the artistic display represented Britain's Industrial Revolution, National Health Service, literary heritage, popular music and culture, and were noted for their vibrant storytelling and use of music.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Two shorter sections drew particular comment, involving a filmed cameo appearance of the Queen with James Bond as her escort, and a live performance by the London Symphony Orchestra joined by comedian Rowan Atkinson.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] These were widely ascribed to Britain's sense of humour.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony featured children and young people in most of its segments, reflecting the "inspire a generation" aspiration of London's original bid for the Games.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The BBC released footage of the entire opening ceremony on 29 October 2012, edited by Danny Boyle and with background extras, along with more than seven hours of sporting highlights and the complete closing ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) approached Danny Boyle to be the director of the ceremony in June 2010, and he immediately accepted.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He said it "felt weirdly more like a ... civic or national responsibility" to take the job.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle acknowledged that the extravagance of the 2008 opening ceremony was an impossible act to follow — "you can't get bigger than Beijing" — and that this realisation had in fact liberated his team creatively.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He said "..obviously I'm not going to try and build on Beijing, because how could you?
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] We can't, and you wouldn't want to, so we're going back to the beginning.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] We're going to try and give the impression that we're rethinking and restarting, because they've (*opening ceremonies*) escalated since Los Angeles in 1984.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They've tried to top themselves each time and you can't do that after Beijing." Beijing's budget had been £65m, whereas London's final budget was £27m, which was twice the original provision.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The London stadium had the same number of seats as Beijing's, but was half the size; this intimacy of scale meant that Boyle felt he could achieve something personal and connecting.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The different sections of the ceremony were designed to reflect aspects of British history and culture, with the title *Isles of Wonder* partly inspired by Shakespeare's play *The Tempest* (particularly Caliban's 'Be not afeard' speech), and partly by the G.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In July 2010, Boyle started brainstorming ideas with designer Mark Tildesley, writer Frank Cottrell-Boyce and costume designer Suttirat Anne Larlarb.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They considered "what was essentially British", with the non-British Larlarb able to offer a view of what the world thought Britain meant.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Cottrell-Boyce had given Boyle a copy of *Pandaemonium*, (named after the capital of Hell in *Paradise Lost*) by Humphrey Jennings, which collated contemporary reports from the Industrial Revolution.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It had become traditional during the opening ceremony to "produce" the Olympic rings in a spectacular manner.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] When Boyle returned to work on the ceremony in the spring of 2011 he asked Rick Smith of Underworld, with whom he had worked on several film projects as well as his theatrical production of Mary Shelley's *Frankenstein*, to be the musical director.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the same time the team moved to the Three Mills studio complex in east London, where a 4x4 metre scale model of the stadium was built.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] For security reasons, a single CGI-assisted version of the ceremony was kept on editor Sascha Dhillon's laptop; anyone needing it had to come to the studio.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The cast included professional performers and 7,500 volunteers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle considered the volunteers to be "the most valuable commodity of all".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In November 2011 they auditioned at Three Mills, and rehearsals began in earnest in spring 2012 at an open-air site at Dagenham (the abandoned Ford plant), often in foul weather.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Although key contributors had to sign non-disclosure agreements and some elements were codenamed, Boyle placed immense trust in the volunteers by asking them simply to "save the surprise" and not leak any information.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Further volunteers were recruited to help with security and marshalling, and to support the technical crew.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Three weeks before the ceremony, Mark Rylance, who was to have taken a leading part, pulled out after a family bereavement and was replaced by Kenneth Branagh.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Olympic Bell, the largest harmonically tuned bell in the world, weighing 23 tonnes, had been cast in brass under the direction of the Whitechapel Bell Foundry by Royal Eijsbouts of the Netherlands, and hung in the Stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was inscribed with a line from Caliban's speech in *The Tempest*: "Be not afeard, the isle is full of noises".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle gave significant emphasis to the London 2012 theme "inspire a generation" and devised a programme relying heavily on children and young people, and built around themes that would relate to the young.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Twenty-five schools in the six original East London host boroughs were used to recruit child volunteers for the performance, and 170 sixth formers (16–18-year-olds), between them speaking more than 50 languages, were recruited from their colleges.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] On 12 June 2012, at a press conference, Boyle had promised a huge set of rural Britain, which was to include a village cricket team, farm animals, a model of Glastonbury Tor, as well as a maypole and a rain-producing cloud.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] His intention was to represent the rural and urban landscape of Britain.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The design was to include a mosh pit at each end of the set, one with people celebrating a rock festival and the other the Last Night of the Proms.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle promised a ceremony with which everyone would feel involved; he said, "I hope it will reveal how peculiar and contrary we are – and how there's also, I hope, a warmth about us." Some of the set was designed with real grass turf and soil.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The use of animals (40 sheep, 12 horses, 3 cows, 2 goats, 10 chickens, 10 ducks, 9 geese and 3 sheep dogs, looked after by 34 animal handlers) drew some criticism from People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle, who was being advised by the RSPCA, assured PETA that the animals would be well cared for.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The overwhelming majority of the music used was British.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The team worked next door to the office of the musical director for the closing ceremony, David Arnold, and so hearing each other's music there was a scramble to claim a particular song first.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rahman, who worked with Boyle on *Slumdog Millionaire* and *127 Hours*, composed a Punjabi song "Nimma Nimma" to showcase Indian influence in the UK, according to Boyle's wishes.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] More Indian music was also scheduled for inclusion in the medley including a Tamil song from the 1989 Bollywood film Ram Lakhan titled "Naanthaan Ungappanda".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Paul McCartney was to be the ceremony's closing act.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Sebastian Coe was instrumental in asking the Queen to take part, responding positively when Boyle first pitched the *Happy and Glorious* film sequence featuring the Queen.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle suggested that the Queen be played either by a lookalike, or by a world-class actress such as Helen Mirren, in a location to double as Buckingham Palace.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Coe asked Princess Anne, a British member of the IOC and LOCOG, what she thought, and she told him to ask the Queen.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Coe presented the idea to the Queen's Deputy Private Secretary.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle was surprised to hear that the Queen would be happy to play herself, and wanted a speaking part.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Filming took place in late March 2012, and *Happy and Glorious* was produced by the BBC, as was the opening film sequence *Journey along the Thames*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Changes were still being made to the programme in the final days before the ceremony: a BMX bike section was dropped due to time constraints, and the "Pandemonium" and "Thanks..Tim" sections were edited down.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In 2016 Boyle recounted how he had come under pressure from Jeremy Hunt, then the Olympics and Culture Secretary, to cut back the NHS section, which he had saved only by threatening to resign and take the volunteers with him.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Two full dress and technical rehearsals took place in the Olympic stadium, on 23 and 25 July, in front of an audience of 60,000 comprising volunteers, cast members' families, competition winners, and others connected to the Games.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle asked them not to "spoil the surprise" by using the hashtag #savethesurprise on social media, keeping the performance a secret for the hundreds of millions who would watch on the Friday night.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Seated in the Royal Box were the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, the Prince of Wales, and other members of the British royal family.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They were accompanied by Archbishop of Canterbury Rowan Williams, Prime Minister David Cameron, Spouse of the Prime Minister Samantha Cameron, former Prime Ministers John Major, Tony Blair and Gordon Brown and Mayor of London Boris Johnson.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Officials of the Olympic movement included President of the IOC Jacques Rogge, LOCOG Chairman Sebastian Coe and members of the IOC.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony was the largest gathering of world leaders for an Olympic and sporting event in history, surpassing that of 2008.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Three multilateral leaders, more than ninety-five heads of state and government and representatives from five organisations and one hundred and twenty countries attended.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At exactly 20:12 BST, the Red Arrows performed a flypast over the Olympic Stadium and then over the concert in Hyde Park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This concert featured artists selected to represent the four nations of the United Kingdom: Duran Duran, Stereophonics, Snow Patrol and Paolo Nutini.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the beginning the stadium contained a rural scene including the model of Glastonbury Tor, a model village and a water wheel, replete with live animals (removed shortly before the ceremony began), and actors portraying working villagers, football and cricket players.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Frank Turner performed three songs ("Sailor's Boots", "Wessex Boy" and "I Still Believe") on the model of Glastonbury Tor, joined by Emily Barker, Ben Marwood and Jim Lockey, as well as his regular backing band the Sleeping Souls.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This performance celebrated Britain's maritime heritage and geographical insularity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony began at 21:00 after a one-minute "60 to 1" countdown film made up of shots of numbers, such as those on house doors, street nameplates, London buses, station platforms and market labels.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The number 39 is seen at the foot of a flight of steps, a reference to John Buchan's novel *The Thirty-Nine Steps*, while the 10 is the door number from 10 Downing Street.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A two-minute film, *Journey along the Thames*, directed by Boyle and produced by the BBC, opened the ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] To the sound of "Surf Solar" by Fuck Buttons, it followed the River Thames from its source to the heart of London, juxtaposing images of contemporary British life with pastoral shots and flashes of scenes from the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The characters Ratty, Mole and Toad from *The Wind in the Willows* were briefly seen, as was a "Monty Python hand" pointing towards London on umbrellas, an InterCity 125 train passing the Olympic rings as crop circles in a field, and a rowing race (to the tune of the "Eton Boating Song").
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At Battersea Power Station a Pink Floyd pig was flying between the towers; the clock sound from another Pink Floyd song "Time" was heard passing Big Ben.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The soundtrack included clips from the theme tune of *The South Bank Show*, "Caprice No.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] 24" (as composed by Andrew Lloyd Webber in his *Variations* fusion album), and the Sex Pistols' "God Save the Queen" as the film followed the route of the band's cruise down the River Thames during the Silver Jubilee.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After lifting to an aerial view of East London mirroring the title sequence of the BBC soap opera *EastEnders*, to the sound of the drum beats from the closing theme, the film flashed down through the Thames Barrier.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It then switched to a sequence filmed outside the stadium shortly before the ceremony, superimposed with posters from previous Summer Olympics (all of them except 1900 Paris, 1936 Berlin, 1984 Los Angeles, and 1996 Atlanta), to a recording of "Map of the Problematique" by Muse.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This ended with a live shot of three cast members holding the posters for the 2012 competition.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] There was then a ten-second countdown in the stadium, with children holding clusters of balloons that burst simultaneously, with the audience shouting out the numbers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bradley Wiggins, who had won the Tour de France five days earlier, opened the ceremony by ringing the Olympic Bell that hung at one end of the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Four upper-atmosphere balloons were released, each expected to carry a set of Olympic rings and a camera up to the mid-stratosphere.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The depiction of rural life already in the arena was billed as "a reminder and a promise of a once and future better life".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] These were inter-cut with footage of notable Rugby Union Home Nations' tries, England's winning drop goal from the 2003 Rugby World Cup Final, and live shots from the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As the last choir performance concluded, vintage London General Omnibus Company stagecoaches entered, carrying businessmen and early industrialists in Victorian dress and top hats, led by Kenneth Branagh as Isambard Kingdom Brunel.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 50 men stepped down from the carriages and surveyed the land approvingly.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After walking onto the Glastonbury Tor, Brunel delivered Caliban's "Be not afeard" speech, reflecting Boyle's introduction to the ceremony in the programme and signifying an aspiration of new industry or a new era in Britain.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This anticipated the next section of the ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section encapsulated British economic and social development from rural economy through the Industrial Revolution to the 1960s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Proceedings were suddenly interrupted by a loud shout, recorded by volunteers during the rehearsals, followed by drumming (the pre-recorded drumming amplified by 965 cast members drumming on inverted household buckets and bins), led by Evelyn Glennie.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The three-tonne oak tree on top of the Glastonbury Tor lifted, and industrial workers emerged from both the Tor's brightly lit interior and the entrances to the stadium, to swell the cast to a total of 2,500 volunteers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] So began what Boyle had called the "biggest scene change in theatre history" and something he had been advised against attempting.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Underworld's "And I Will Kiss" began to play, as the cast rolled away the grass and other rural props.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Seven smoking chimney stacks with accompanying steeplejacks rose from the ground, along with other industrial machinery: five beam engines, six looms, a crucible and a water wheel (one of the few items left from the rural scene).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle said that this section celebrated the "tremendous potential" afforded by the advancements of the Victorian era.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It also included a minute's silence in remembrance of the loss of life of both world wars, featuring British "Tommies" and shots of poppies, during which the names of the Accrington Pals were shown on the stadium screens.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Unprompted, members of the audience stood in respect during this segment.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Also included were real-life Chelsea Pensioners, the Grimethorpe Colliery Band, and a group of Pearly Kings and Queens.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As the noise level and tension built, driven by the relentless rhythm of the music and the drumming, participants mimed repetitive mechanical movements associated with industrial processes such as weaving.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Four glowing orange rings gradually began to be carried high above the stadium toward its centre on overhead wires, and then the ring seemingly being cast and forged in the arena began to rise.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The five rings converged, still glowing and accompanied by steam and firework effects to give the impression that they were of hot metal.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] When the five rings formed the Olympic symbol above the stadium, they ignited and rained fire in silver and gold.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The image of the Olympic rings in flame became the iconic image of the ceremony, reproduced in newspapers and web stories around the world.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A short film directed by Boyle and produced by the BBC, called *Happy and Glorious* (after a line in the national anthem), featured the character James Bond, played by then-Bond actor Daniel Craig, entering the front gate of Buckingham Palace in a London black cab.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] His entrance (accompanied by an arrangement of Handel's "Arrival of the Queen of Sheba") is noticed by Brazilian children (a nod to Rio de Janeiro, which was to be the next summer Games host city) in the throne room.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bond meets Elizabeth II (who played herself, acknowledging Bond with the words, "Good evening, Mr Bond") in her audience room at the palace, walks with her out of the building and into a waiting AgustaWestland AW139 helicopter.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The film followed the helicopter across London, with shots of a cheering crowd on The Mall, Nelson's Column, the Palace of Westminster with an animated Winston Churchill statue in Parliament Square, and of the Thames past the London Eye, St Paul's Cathedral, the financial district City of London.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The helicopter then passed through Tower Bridge, accompanied by the Dambusters March.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The film finished with Bond and the Queen apparently jumping from a real helicopter live above the stadium, accompanied by the "James Bond Theme".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, along with Rogge, were then introduced to the audience.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen was wearing the same dress as in the film, as if she had just arrived with Bond.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The idea of the royal helicopter jump was first pitched by director Danny Boyle to Sebastian Coe, who loved it so much he took it to Edward Young, Private Secretary to the Queen, at Buckingham Palace in the summer of 2011.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Young "listened sagely, laughed, and promised to ask the boss".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Word came back to Coe that the Queen would love to take part.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Young, Boyle and Coe agreed to keep the plan secret so as not to spoil the surprise.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] For the scenes with the helicopter, the Queen was doubled by actress Julia McKenzie, and for the parachute jump by BASE jumper and stuntman Gary Connery wearing a dress, hat, jewellery and with a handbag.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The helicopter had flown to the stadium from Stapleford Aerodrome in Essex, piloted by Marc Wolff.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Union Flag was then raised by members of the British Armed Forces, while the first and third verses of the national anthem were performed *a cappella* by the Kaos Signing Choir for Deaf and Hearing Children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The first part of this sequence celebrated the National Health Service ("the institution which more than any other unites our nation", according to the programme), which had been founded in the year of the previous London Games in 1948.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Six hundred dancers, some of whom were NHS staff, along with 1,200 volunteers, some recruited from British hospitals, entered along with children on 320 hospital beds, some of which functioned as trampolines.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Watching from the tor were specially invited hospital staff and nine child patients from Great Ormond Street Hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The blankets on the beds illuminated and the beds were arranged to depict a child's face with a smile and a tear (the Hospital Children's Charity's logo).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The acronym "GOSH" then changed into the initials "NHS", turning into the shape of a crescent moon as the children were hushed to sleep and read books by the nurses.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sequence then moved on to celebrate British children's literature.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Barrie's *Peter Pan* (whose copyright was given to Great Ormond Street Hospital).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Child Catcher appeared amongst the children, followed by giant puppet representations of villains from British children's literature: the Queen of Hearts, Captain Hook, Cruella de Vil, and Lord Voldemort.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Minutes later, 32 women playing Mary Poppins descended with their umbrellas, as the villains deflated and the actors resumed dancing.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The music for this sequence included partially rearranged sections from *Tubular Bells* (with a giant set of tubular bells at the rear of the stage), *Tubular Bells III* and, after the villains had been driven away by the Mary Poppins characters, *In Dulci Jubilo*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] During this performance the children in pyjamas jumped up and down on their brightly lit beds, creating a memorable image amid the darkness of the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sequence concluded with a pale, gigantic baby's head, with a rippling sheet for its body, in the centre of the arena.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This celebrated the Scottish pioneers of obstetric ultrasound imaging.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Simon Rattle was then introduced to conduct the London Symphony Orchestra in a performance of Vangelis's "Chariots of Fire", as a tribute to the British film industry with Rowan Atkinson reprising his role as Mr.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bean, comically playing a repeated note on a synthesiser.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He then lapsed into a filmed dream sequence in which he joined the runners from the film *Chariots of Fire*, beating them in their iconic run along West Sands at St Andrews by riding in a car, rejoining the race and tripping the front runner.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Danny Boyle later said: "It wasn't actually Mr.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Strictly speaking, the name of his character was Derek." In 2021's *Happy Birthday Mr Bean* documentary, Atkinson also stated that the performance was not actually intended to be the character Mr.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This sequence celebrated British popular music and culture, paying homage to each decade since the 1960s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] To the accompaniment of the BBC newsreel theme "Girls in Grey" and the theme tune from *The Archers*, a young mother and son arrive in a Mini Cooper at a full-size replica of a modern British house.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 1987 "don't worry about a hurricane" weather forecast by Michael Fish was shown on the big screens as rain suddenly poured on the house, followed by "Push the Button", by Sugababes.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] During this track images of the Underground were projected onto the house and former London Mayor Ken Livingstone was briefly seen driving the train.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Throughout the sequence cast members were texting each other or placing social networking status updates on the Internet.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Frankie and June first notice each other as a snippet from "Wonderful Tonight" by Eric Clapton plays, but when Frankie saw that June had dropped her phone on the Tube, he set off to return it (communicating using last number redial to her sister's phone).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the close, while "Heaven" by Emeli Sandé was played, the larger house was raised to reveal Tim Berners-Lee working at a NeXT Computer, like the one on which he invented the World Wide Web.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He tweeted "This is for everyone", instantly spelt out in LED lights around the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The programme explained "Music connects us with each other and with the most important moments in our lives.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] One of the things that makes those connections possible is the World Wide Web".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle wanted to honour Berners-Lee for having made the World Wide Web free and available to everyone (hence the tweet), rather than seeking a commercial profit from it.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A filmed sequence showed extracts from the torch relay around the UK, to the music "I Heard Wonders" by David Holmes.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This then cut live to show David Beckham driving a dramatically illuminated motor boat down the River Thames and under Tower Bridge, to fireworks, while footballer Jade Bailey held on to the torch in the boat.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section had been rehearsed on 24 July 2012 when the close-up shots were pre-recorded, and was directed by Stephen Daldry.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] There was then a tribute to "..friends and family of those in the stadium who cannot be here tonight", including the victims of the "7/7" 2005 London bombings (on the day after London had been awarded the Games).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Photos of people who had died were displayed on screens as a memorial, accompanied by an excerpt from Brian Eno's ambient work "An Ending (Ascent)".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The hymn "Abide with Me" was then sung by Emeli Sandé while a group of dancers choreographed by and including Akram Khan performed a contemporary dance on the theme of mortality.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Parade of Nations of athletes (drawn from the 10,490 competing) and officials from 204 nations (and also the "Independent Olympic Athletes") was led, according to custom, by the Greek team, followed by other competing countries in alphabetical order, and finally the host nation Great Britain.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Welsh drum and bass DJ High Contrast mixed and sequenced the music for the athletes' parade.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Once all of the athletes were inside the stadium, seven billion small pieces of paper were dropped from a Westland helicopter, each piece representing one person on Earth.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Each nation's flag was planted on the Glastonbury Tor.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Once the athletes had gathered in the centre of the stadium, Arctic Monkeys performed "I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor" and The Beatles' "Come Together", the latter while 75 cyclists circled the stadium with wings lit by LEDs representing Doves of Peace.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Doves were traditionally released at Olympic opening ceremonies, although real birds have not been used since 1992.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A single dove cyclist, his beak painted yellow in honour of Bradley Wiggins, appeared to fly out of the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The formal part of the ceremony was introduced by Sebastian Coe, speaking from the Tor and surrounded by flags of the participating nations.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He welcomed the watching world to London.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He expressed pride in being British and part of the Olympic movement, and said that the Olympics "brings together the people of the world...to celebrate what is best about mankind".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He continued to speak of the "truth and drama" of sport, and then thanked Britain for "making all this possible".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge responded by thanking London, stating that it was the third time that London had held the Games, following 1908, held at short notice when Rome was unable to do so (after a volcanic eruption), and 1948 three years after the end of World War II.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge thanked the thousands of volunteers, to huge cheers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He announced that for the first time in Olympic history, every team had female participants.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge acknowledged the important role the UK had played as "the birthplace of modern sport", codifying its "fair play" ethos and building sport into the school curriculum.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He appealed to athletes to play fairly and be drug-free, according to the values of Baron de Coubertin, reminding them that they were role models who would "inspire a generation".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After expressing these sentiments again briefly in French, he invited the Queen to open the Games.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen declared the competition officially open, immediately followed by a trumpet fanfare based on a theme from *Tubular Bells* by Mike Oldfield and then a fireworks display.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 2012 ceremony was the second time the Queen had opened an Olympic Games, the first being the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal in her capacity as Queen of Canada.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was also the first time any individual had opened a Summer Olympics twice (two more Olympiads had been opened on her behalf, with a further two Winter Games opened on her behalf).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The flag paused in front of Muhammad Ali (invited to represent "respect, confidence, conviction, dedication, generosity and spiritual strength"), who held it for a few moments.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The flag was received by a colour guard of Her Majesty's Armed Forces and hoisted to the Olympic Anthem, performed by the LSO and the Grimethorpe Colliery Band.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A brief reprise of "And I will Kiss" commenced the Olympic Oaths, taken by taekwondo athlete Sarah Stevenson on behalf of the athletes, by British AIBA Referee Mik Basi on behalf of the officials, and by Eric Farrell on behalf of the coaches.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section was named after the song of the same name by The Smiths.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The motorboat driven by David Beckham arrived with the Olympic Flame via the Limehouse Cut and the Lee Navigation.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Steve Redgrave lit his torch from that on the boat, and carried it into the stadium through an honour guard of 500 of the construction workers who had built the Olympic Park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He passed the flame on to a team of seven young people, each nominated by a famous British Olympian to convey the Games' aim to "inspire a generation".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Six of the team were athletes, and the seventh was a volunteer young ambassador.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The teenagers made a lap of the stadium, each carrying the torch in turn, while Alex Trimble, lead singer of Two Door Cinema Club, performed "Caliban's Dream" with the Dockhead Choir, Only Men Aloud, Elizabeth Roberts, and Esme Smith.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This had been written especially for the ceremony by Rick Smith of Underworld.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Each young athlete was greeted by their nominating Olympian (watched by 260 British medallists from previous summer and winter Games since London 1948) and presented with their own torch, which was then lit from the flame.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The young athletes lit some of the petals, and when the flame had spread to all of them, the pipes rose slowly from the floor of the stadium and converged to form the cauldron.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The cauldron designed by Thomas Heatherwick was described as "one of the best-kept secrets of the opening ceremony": until this point, its design, location, and who would light it had not been revealed.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A flurry of spectacular fireworks accompanied by Pink Floyd's song "Eclipse" was supported by images of memorable Olympic victories shown on the big screens, with the stadium pixels showing Jesse Owens running.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The climax of this section was a live view of the Olympic rings 34 kilometres (21 miles) above the Earth, transmitted from one of the balloons launched three and a half hours earlier.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sky was then lit by searchlights piercing the smoke (another iconic London image) from the fireworks, the Orbit tower was illuminated.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Paul McCartney and his band performed the closing section of "The End", and then "Hey Jude", with its chorus sung by the audience to close the ceremony at 00:46 BST.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The eclectic programme of music was chosen to showcase almost exclusively British music with pieces representing the UK's four nations.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It included classical works by British composers such as Hubert Parry, and performances by UK choirs and orchestras.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The focus was mainly on music of the 1960s onwards, causing one Chinese journalist to ask: "Will this be the most rock and roll opening ceremony ever?".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Rick Smith and Underworld composed pieces for the ceremony, including "And I Will Kiss" used during the "Pandemonium" section, and "Caliban's Dream" heard during the lighting of the cauldron.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These were favourably reviewed; in *The Guardian*, Michael Hann wrote "Underworld ... had a bit of a triumph: the builds and fades they learned in the world of dance music lent the sometimes overwhelming visual spectacle a sense of structure".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Bells were a theme of the opening day of the Olympics, starting at 8:12 am with artist Martin Creed's *Work No.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 1197: All the Bells*, when bells were rung across the UK including forty strikes of Big Ben.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] "The sound of bells is the sound of England", Boyle had told volunteers during rehearsal.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Much of the music for the ceremony contained "bell" references, linking to the large bell forged for the ceremony and evoking bells as "the sound of freedom and peace".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Modified sequences based on the traditional British eight-bell peal underlaid "And I Will Kiss" and carried through into the "Tubular Bells"/NHS section, with handbells and a tolling large bell featured on "Caliban's Dream" and at key points in the ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A handbell chime also played after the close, as the stadium emptied.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle approached many of the artists personally, to see if they would be interested in performing, and he also flew to Barbados for an hour-long meeting with Mike Oldfield.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A few turned him down, including Elvis Costello and David Bowie.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The performing artists were paid a nominal £1 fee to make their contracts legally binding.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The pre-recorded soundtrack *Isles of Wonder* was released on iTunes at midnight of 28 July 2012, with a two-disc CD set released on 2 August.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Within two days, the download album had topped the iTunes album charts in Britain, France, Belgium and Spain, and reached No.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 5 in the United States, as well as being No.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Rick Smith's concluding comment in the CD cover notes was: "The isle is full of noises.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The main loading of the stadium started on 10 May and took ten weeks of what was the wettest summer for a hundred years, posing considerable challenges.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Dismantling the staging took just sixty hours.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The infield staging area was 2.5 metres high, and had to accommodate the elements revealed during the ceremony, such as the chimneys and beam engines from "Pandemonium", and the cauldron.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] To ensure that it remained secret, the cauldron was code-named "Betty", and installed and tested at night.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The stadium was rigged with a one million watt sound system and more than 500 speakers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Some 15,000 square metres (3.7 acres) of staging and 12,956 props were used, as well as 7,346 square metres (1.815 acres) of turf including crops.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 70,799 25 centimetre (10 inch) pixel panels were placed around the stadium, including between every seat.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Each panel connected to a central computer and was fitted with nine full-colour LED pixels by Tait Technology.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These enabled images to be broadcast during the performance, such as of a 1960s go-go dancer, a London Underground train, and a representation of the birth of the internet.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The audience was also able to participate by waving the paddles to create a twinkling effect.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These animations were designed by 59 Productions and the video animations were produced by Chinese company Crystal CG.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The 2D to 3D transformation and mapping of video content onto the panels were done by Avolites Media media server consoles.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Technical director Piers Shepperd masterminded the complex change from rural to industrial during "Pandemonium".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The seven inflatable chimneys were made by Airworks, and varied in height (three were 22-metre (72 ft), two were 23-metre (75 ft) and two were 30-metre (98 ft) high).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] They were made of soft fabric, with an outer layer of printed brick pattern.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Each contained four industrial fans at the base to inflate them, and a smoke machine near the top, and were hoisted into the air from the overhead rigs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Life-size beam engines were constructed onstage by teams of stage hands and members of the Volunteer Staging Team.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] At the climax of "Pandemonium", in the Olympic ring forging scene, amber lights lit in sequence created the illusion of a 30-metre (98 ft) molten steel river, with pyrotechnic smoke and dry ice as steam.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The original grass floor surface had been removed to reveal a giant stylised map of London.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Working alongside the professional crew were more than 800 volunteers; some were production arts students from British drama schools.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Many had been working on the Olympic and Paralympic ceremonies since early 2012 at the Three Mills Studios and Dagenham rehearsal sites, before moving to the Stadium on 16 June.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The thousands of cast were cued and co-ordinated by directions received through earphones ("in-ear monitors"), and adjustments were made during the performance: for example, during Pandemonium extra volunteers were sent to make sure all the turf was cleared on time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The earphones also carried a continuous electronic metronomic four-beat to keep everyone walking and moving in time with the music.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In July 2013 it was revealed that on the morning of the ceremony, Britain's surveillance headquarters GCHQ had detected a credible cyber attack threat that could have killed the lighting system in the stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Counter-measures were taken, and in the afternoon contingency plans were discussed with government ministers at a meeting in the Cabinet Office briefing room.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] However, this attack never materialised.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC's coverage started at 19:00 and continued uninterrupted until 00:50.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC audience averaged about 24.46 million viewers and peaked at approximately 26.9 million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This was the largest average audience for any broadcast since 1996 and one of the top 20 most-watched UK television broadcasts of all time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] David Stringer of Associated Press described the coverage as "a success...so far, the BBC's ambitious – and technically tricky – Olympic plan has worked almost without a flaw." Euan Ferguson of *The Observer* commented that "Coverage of the Olympics so far ... has been near perfect".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] However, Clive James was critical of the build-up programme, presented by Gary Lineker and Sue Barker.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Commentators for the BBC were Huw Edwards, Hazel Irvine and Trevor Nelson, the latter criticised by Andy Dawson of the *Daily Mirror* as floundering "like a ventriloquist's dummy pumped full of low-grade ketamine".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Private talks were held between Boyle and BBC commentators in the run-up to the ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle was unhappy with a voiceover being imposed on the ceremony, which he wanted viewers to be able to enjoy without commentary.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC offered several options including "no commentary" coverage for both its TV and online transmissions.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Audio description was also provided with commentary by Nick Mullins.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Nearly 41 million US viewers watched NBC's coverage of the event.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Criticism was levelled at its decision to tape-delay this broadcast, and not make a live version available even to cable and web users.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There were frequent interruptions by commercial breaks.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Many US viewers looked for other ways to watch (such as the live BBC feed), despite both NBC and the IOC vowing to crack down on unauthorised streams.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] More significant criticism was levelled at NBC for cutting to a Ryan Seacrest interview with Michael Phelps during the "memorial wall" tribute including commemoration of the victims of the 7/7 London bombings, which was seen as disrespectful and insensitive.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] An NBC spokesman said the network had left out that segment because its programming was "tailored for the US audience".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There was also criticism of commentators Matt Lauer and Meredith Vieira for suggesting that the Queen had actually jumped out of a helicopter.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Vieira and Lauer admitted to not knowing that Tim Berners-Lee was the inventor of the World Wide Web, as she commented "If you haven't heard of him, we haven't either", before Lauer told the audience to Google him.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These failings were picked up on Twitter during the broadcast with the hashtag #nbcfail.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was recorded by three separate broadcasters: the BBC, the Olympic Broadcasting Services (directed by the Finnish state broadcaster YLE on behalf of the OBS), and by independent production company Done and Dusted, hired by LOCOG and working under Boyle's direction.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This was the first time that an independent production company had been used for an Olympic ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This situation led to some tension, as Boyle wanted more artistic control and felt he was getting no co-operation from the OBS.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] He criticised the OBS coverage during his commentary for the BBC DVD.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In addition, the BBC filmed some of the pre-recorded parts of the ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The filming was directed for television by Hamish Hamilton, who described it as "easily the most difficult job of my life".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC released footage of the entire ceremony on 29 October 2012, edited by Danny Boyle and with background extras, filling more than one disc of a five DVD or Blu-ray disc set, which also contained more than seven hours of sporting highlights as well as the complete closing ceremony.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A "BBC commentary-free" option for the opening ceremony is available on the DVD, as well as a commentary track by Danny Boyle and Frank Cottrell-Boyce.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Although praise came from across the political spectrum, a few on the British political right were unhappy.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Aidan Burley, a Conservative MP, denounced the ceremony on Twitter as "leftie multicultural crap".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Burley's comments were dismissed by many fellow Conservatives, including David Cameron and Boris Johnson.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Foreign reaction was overwhelmingly positive.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The New York Times* said the ceremony was "hilariously quirky ... a wild jumble of the celebratory and the fanciful; the conventional and the eccentric; and the frankly off-the-wall".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *Forbes* called it Boyle's "love song to Britain", while *Sports Illustrated* noted its political aspects, calling it "a celebration of protest and dissent".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The Sydney Morning Herald* said it was "an unforgettable start ... at once subversive and sublime" and *The Times of India* said that "London presented a vibrant picture of Great Britain's rich heritage and culture".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The Chinese news agency *Xinhua* described the ceremony as "dazzling" and an "eccentric and exuberant celebration of British history, art and culture".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Russian President Putin said the ceremony was "wonderful and unforgettable".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] French sports newspaper *L'Équipe* wrote that the ceremony "took the classic from such events and had fun with them", while *Le Parisien* said it "was magnificent, inventive and offbeat drawing heavily on the roots of British identity".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Germany's *Die Welt* hailed it as "spectacular, glitzy but also provoking and moving".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Chinese news CCTV-4 said the ceremony was a "stunning feast for the eyes".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] South Korea's Yonhap said it was "by turns dramatic, imaginative, humorous and solemn" and "weaved the story of the country's past, present and future".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Singapore's *Straits Times* said it was a "grand show" noteworthy for both "scale" and "authenticity".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The Australian* praised a "glorious pandemonium devoted to London's thriving, chaotic energy ... deliberately revelling in the chaos of Britain's free society and popular culture".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] France's *Le Figaro* said the ceremony reflected "the best contributions that Britain has given to the world ... its sense of humour, its music, and of course sport".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation said it was a "rocking, rollicking, sometimes quiet and brooding ceremony".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Qatar's *The Peninsula* said that London did a "spectacular job" making the ceremony a "memorable event".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In an end of the year review, British magazine *Q* said "It could all have been so different.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] As the London 2012 Summer Olympics approached, the tide of scepticism seemed almost irreversible.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There was the heavy-handed sponsorship, the draconian security, the ticketing problems, the ballooning budget, and the lurking fear that the Opening Ceremony might be, in director Danny Boyle's pungent description, 'shite'.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It took less than four hours on the night of Friday 27 July to turn the whole country around.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The writer of the ceremony, Frank Cottrell-Boyce, said: "People around us thought it might need defending, so I was told to do press the next morning.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] I was completely surprised *[by the positive response]*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] At no point did he show any feeling that it was going to be anything but amazing.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In December 2012 the culture critic of *The Guardian* picked the ceremony as "best art event of the year".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A British public survey by Samsung voted it the second most inspiring television moment of all time, second only to the 1969 Apollo 11 Moon landing.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A Digital Spy survey of more than 25,000 overwhelmingly voted the ceremony as the entertainment highlight of 2012.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was the second most-mentioned entertainment event on the internet in 2012, with just over six million mentions, coming second to the Grammy Awards.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC reported that it was the most requested item from 2012 on its iPlayer on-demand service, with 3.3 million requests.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was identified by some commentators as precipitating a new mood in the United Kingdom: it "had barely finished before it had become a byword for a new approach, not only to British culture but to Britishness itself.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Politicians would soon be referring to it, using it as shorthand for a new kind of patriotism that does not lament a vanished Britain but loves the country that has changed.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle's ceremony was hailed from (almost) all sides...for providing a nation that had grown used to mocking its myriad flaws with a new, unfamiliarly positive view of itself ...
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It was, perhaps, this lack of cynicism that people responded to ...
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] So used to British irony and detachment, it felt refreshing to witness an unembarrassed, positive case for this country.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle himself says this was the most important thing he took away from the Olympic experience: "How important it is to believe in something.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Business leaders also took inspiration from the event, admiring its risk-taking and creative freedom, as well as the trust placed in and loyalty inspired from the workers and volunteers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Reviewing the 2014 Winter Olympics opening ceremony at Sochi, Russia, Owen Gibson of *The Guardian* observed that with his "complex, intimate snapshot of 'who we were, who we are and who we wish to be'", Boyle "rewrote the rule book for opening ceremonies".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Alan Turing Institute was founded following a letter from the Council for Science and Technology (CST) to the UK prime minister (7 June 2013), describing the "Age of Algorithms".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The letter presented a case that "The Government, working with the universities and industry, should create a National Centre to promote advanced research and translational work in algorithms and the application of data science".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Alan Turing Institute fits into a complex organisational landscape that includes the Open Data Institute, the Digital Catapult and infrastructure investments.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The role of the institute is to provide the expertise and fundamental research into data science and artificial intelligence needed to solve real-world problems.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Alan Turing Institute has since 2021 run an annual event called AI UK, which is described as a national showcase of data science and artificial intelligence.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The organisation's intranet is called Mathison, which was Alan Turing's middle name.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In 2015, Lloyd's Register Foundation became the institute's first strategic partner, providing a grant of £10 million over five years to support research into the engineering applications of big data.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In March 2023, the Turing Institute announced a new strategy, dubbed "Turing 2.0" where AI was to focus on health, the environment and national security.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Following the release of the strategy, an all-male team of four senior academics was hired to deliver on the new strategy, leading to a letter signed by 180 staff members to express serious concerns about the institute's approach to diversity and inclusion.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In October 2024, the Institute started a redundancy consultation process, affecting around 140 of the 440 staff members.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In December 2024, 93 employees of the Alan Turing Institute sent a letter to the board of the institute to expresses no confidence in the body's executive leadership and asked the board to intervene.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In addition to concerns about gender diversity and the redundancy round, the letter mentions the institute's sense of direction as issues.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Furthermore, it outlines how a lack of accountability and transparency, as well as poor decision making by the executive, are leading to a catastrophic decline in trust in leadership and rising levels of stress and burnout across employees.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Reportedly, an internal review by the institute mirrors these conclusions.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] On 4 July 2025, it was reported that the technology secretary Peter Kyle demanded a further overhaul of the Alan Turing Institute, calling for a focus on defence and national security, and a change of leadership.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In a letter to the chair of the Turing, Kyle reportedly wrote that "it remains clear that further action is needed to ensure the ATI meets its full potential".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Around that time, ATI was undergoing a restructuring with about 50 staff notified that they were at risk of redundancy.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] A letter in August 2025 from Kyle called for leadership change, as well as repeating his call for the change of focus.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] He warned long-term funding could be reviewed in 2026.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Guardian and BBC reported that staff of the ATI "have raised concerns about the organisation's governance and internal culture" in a whistleblowing complaint to the Charity Commission, after staff also complained to the institute's main funder, UK Research and Innovation (UKRI).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The BBC reported on the internal response to staff by Turing's Chair Doug Gurr and CEO Jean Innes, claiming a commitment to "honesty, integrity and transparency" that was viewed by the whistleblowers as "performative".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] On 4 September 2025, the institute announced that Innes will be stepping down as the CEO.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In an interview with the BBC, published on 28 October 2025, Gurr claimed that the whistleblower complaints had been "independently investigated", but did not name which third party had conducted that investigation.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In March 2026, the Charity Commission issued formal regulatory advice and guidance to the trustees of the institute and closed the case without a statutory inquiry.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In February 2026, it was announced that George Williamson, head of His Majesty's Government Communications Centre at the time, would start as the new chief executive of the Turing from May 2026, further deepening the institute's shift towards defence and national security.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] On 1 April 2026, the institute announced that chair Doug Gurr had resigned to become chair of the Competition and Markets Authority and that former co-deputy chair Vanessa Lawrence would fill the role of chair in the interim.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In April 2026, it was reported that the UKRI had conducted a review which found that ATI was underperforming in strategy and value for money, with the reviewer saying ATI needed to be "focused, effective and aligned to national need".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Alan Turing Institute is an independent private-sector legal entity, operating not-for-profit and as a charity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] It is a joint venture among the University of Cambridge, the University of Edinburgh, the University of Oxford, University College London (UCL) and the University of Warwick, selected on the basis of international peer review.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In 2018, the institute was joined by eight additional university partners: Queen Mary University of London, University of Leeds, University of Manchester, University of Newcastle, University of Southampton, University of Birmingham, University of Exeter and University of Bristol.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC), the primary funder of the institute, is also a member of the joint venture.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The primary responsibility for establishing the Alan Turing Institute has been assigned to the EPSRC, with continuing engagement in the shaping of the institute from the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) and the Government Office for Science.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In 2024 there were 440 staff members, and as of 2025, "over 400 researchers collaborate[d] at the Turing", without information how many were actually employed.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Funding for the creation of the institute came from a £600m investment for the "Eight Great Technologies", and specifically so-called "big data", signalled by the UK Government in 2013 and announced by George Osborne, Chancellor of the Exchequer, in the 2014 budget.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The bulk of the investment in "big data" was directed to computational infrastructure.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Of the remainder, £42m was allocated to the institute to cover the first five years of its operation.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The five founder universities each contributed £5m to the institute.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Further funding has come primarily through grants from Research Councils, university partners and from strategic and other partnerships.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In June 2021, the EPSRC awarded the institute £10 million, on behalf of UK Research and Innovation, for 2021/22.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The government's 2024 Spring Budget provided a further £100m, spread over five years, directed towards applying data science and artificial intelligence to healthcare, protecting the environment and bolstering national defence.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Soon after, a review by the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council recommended improvements in financial oversight of funding for the institute.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] Concurrently with the selection of founder universities, the EPSRC initiated a process to find a "location partner".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] The resulting selection of the British Library in London was announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer in December 2014 during the launch of the Knowledge Quarter, a partnership of organisations in and around the King's Cross area of the capital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] In February 2023, plans for a new building were approved by the local council.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alan-turing-institute] As of 2023, the Alan Turing Institute was housed within the current British Library building, but it was anticipated it would occupy new premises in a development planned on land between the Francis Crick Institute and library.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The **Anna Freud** (formerly the **Anna Freud National Centre for Children and Families**) is a child mental health research, training, treatment and policy advisory charity based in London, United Kingdom.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre aims to transform mental health provision in the UK by improving the quality, accessibility and effectiveness of treatment, bringing together leaders in neuroscience, mental health, social care and education.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] It is closely associated with University College London (UCL) and Yale University.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Princess of Wales is its royal patron.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The chair of trustees is the philanthropist Michael Samuel MBE and the chief executive is Eamon McCrory OBE.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Hampstead Child Therapy Course was started by Anna Freud, daughter of Dr.Sigmund Freud, in 1947.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Students included Joyce McDougall, who had her first experience of intensive analysis with children whilst on the course.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Hampstead Child Therapy Course and Clinic was founded in 1952 by Anna Freud, Dorothy Burlingham, and Helen Ross, becoming the first child psychoanalytic centre for observational research, teaching and learning.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] It was established as a charity with the purpose of providing training, treatment and research in child psychoanalysis.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] After Anna Freud's death in 1982, it was renamed in her honour.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] In 2012 it stated that its aim is to secure its position as the leading psychoanalytic innovator and provider of mental health treatment to children and families in Europe.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre provides short-term and long-term specialist treatments for children suffering from mental health problems.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre conducts research in collaboration with the Yale University Child Study Center and the Menninger Department of Psychiatry at Baylor College of Medicine.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre's historic links with Yale University have been renewed through the recently established Anna Freud Centre/Yale Child Study Center Bridge Programme.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Research teams from the Menninger Department of Psychiatry, the Anna Freud and Yale Child Study Center form a developmental and clinical psychoanalytically-inspired research consortium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre also hosts the Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) Evidence Based Practice Unit, an interdisciplinary research unit which is part of UCL.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Its research focuses on supporting the implementation of evidence-based practice and also gathering practice-based evidence for mental health interventions.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Current projects include a national evaluation of therapies (part of the Children and Young People's Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme); research on shared decision making; and the development of models for resource need as part of the CAMHS Payment by Results project.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Research activity can be funded by public bodies (for example the Education for Wellbeing project is funded by the Department for Education).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Individual charities commission the Anna Freud to carry out evaluative research into the effectiveness of their own services (for example 42nd Street (mental health charity) commissioned the Anna Freud to review their TC42 service in 2020).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Research can be based on collaboration with other bodies (for example a study into adoption working with Coram and Great Ormond Street Hospital).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] In June 2003 a study conducted jointly by the Anna Freud, Great Ormond Street Hospital and Coram Family Adoption Services on the way in which abused children can have their faith in adults restored through adoption was published.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] In September 2009 a collaborative project involving the Anna Freud, Kids Company and UCL was launched to study what happens to the brains of children who have suffered early trauma.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Centre also offers an extensive range of short courses.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] The Anna Freud Library supports the academic, clinical and research activities at the Centre.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] It currently holds approximately 2,000 books covering both historical and contemporary psychoanalytic material, and subscribes to 22 journal titles.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Electronic access to research publications is also available.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/anna-freud-centre] Notable alumni of the Centre include Erna Furman.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The **Arsenal Football Club** is an English professional football club based in Islington, North London, England.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] They compete in the Premier League, the top tier of English football.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Domestically, Arsenal have won 14 league titles (including one unbeaten), a record 14 FA Cups, 2 League Cups, 17 FA Community Shields and a Football League Centenary Trophy.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In European football, they have won one European Cup Winners' Cup and one Inter-Cities Fairs Cup.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In terms of trophies won, it is the third-most successful club in English football, and one of the most successful clubs in world football.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal was the first club from southern England to join the Football League in 1893, officially joining the First Division in 1904.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal carries the longest active streak continuously in the top division (over 105 years and counting) and completed the 20th century with the highest average league position of any club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal has won the second-most top-flight matches in English football history.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 1930s, Arsenal won five League Championships and two FA Cups, with another FA Cup and two more Championships coming after the war.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1970–71, it won its first League and FA Cup double.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Between 1989 and 2005, the club won five league titles and five FA Cups, including two more doubles.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Between 1998 and 2017, Arsenal qualified for the UEFA Champions League for an English football record of nineteen consecutive seasons.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club finished as Champions League runners-up in 2006 and 2026.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1886, munitions workers at the Royal Arsenal in Woolwich founded the club as Dial Square.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1913, the club crossed the city to the Arsenal Stadium in Highbury, becoming close neighbours of Tottenham Hotspur, thus creating the North London derby.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Herbert Chapman won the club its first silverware, and his legacy enabled a trophy-laden period in the 1930s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He helped introduce the WM formation, floodlights, and shirt numbers; he also added the white sleeves and brighter red to the club's jersey.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsène Wenger was the club's longest-serving manager and won the most trophies.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He won a record seven FA Cups, and his third and final title-winning team set an English record for the longest top-flight unbeaten league run at 49 games between 2003 and 2004, receiving the nickname "The Invincibles".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 2006, the club moved to the nearby Emirates Stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With an annual revenue of £616.6m in the 2023–24 season, Arsenal was estimated to be worth US$3.4 billion by *Forbes*, making it the world's eighth-most valuable football club, while also being one of the most followed sport teams in the world on social media.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The motto of the club is *Victoria Concordia Crescit*, Latin for "Victory Through Harmony".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In October 1886, Scotsman David Danskin and fifteen fellow munitions workers in Woolwich formed the Dial Square Football Club, named after a workshop at the heart of the Royal Arsenal complex.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Each member contributed sixpence, and Danskin also added three shillings to help form the club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Dial Square played their first match on 11 December 1886 against the Eastern Wanderers and won 6–0.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club had been renamed Royal Arsenal by January 1887, and its first home was Plumstead Common, though they spent most of their time playing at the Manor Ground.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Their first trophies were the Kent Senior Cup and London Charity Cup in 1889–90 and the London Senior Cup in 1890–91; these were the only county association trophies Arsenal won during their time in South East London.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1891, Royal Arsenal became the first London club to turn professional.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Royal Arsenal was renamed for the second time upon becoming a limited liability company in 1893.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] They registered their new name, Woolwich Arsenal, with the Football League when the club ascended later that year.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Woolwich Arsenal was the first southern member of the Football League, starting out in the Second Division and reaching the First Division in 1904.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Falling attendances, due to financial difficulties among the munitions workers and the arrival of more accessible football clubs elsewhere in the city, led the club close to bankruptcy by 1910.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Businessmen Henry Norris and William Hall became involved in the club, and sought to move them elsewhere.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1913, soon after relegation back to the Second Division, the club moved across the river to the new Arsenal Stadium in Highbury.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1919, the Football League controversially voted to promote The Arsenal, instead of relegated local rivals Tottenham Hotspur, into the newly enlarged First Division, despite only finishing fifth in the Second Division's last pre-war season of 1914–15.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Later that year, The Arsenal started dropping "The" in official documents, gradually shifting its name for the final time towards Arsenal, as it is generally known today.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With a new home and First Division football, attendances were more than double those at the Manor Ground, and Arsenal's budget grew rapidly.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With record-breaking spending and gate receipts, Arsenal quickly became known as the Bank of England club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's location and record-breaking salary offer lured star Huddersfield Town manager Herbert Chapman in 1925.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Over the next five years, Chapman built a revolutionary new Arsenal.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Firstly, he appointed an enduring new trainer, Tom Whittaker who would one day rise to become a fabled Arsenal manager himself.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With the help of player Charlie Buchan, implemented the nascent WM formation which would serve as a stable bedrock to his outfit.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He also captured generational young talents such as Cliff Bastin and Eddie Hapgood, whilst also lavishing Highbury's high income on stars such as David Jack and Alex James.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Transformed, Chapman's Arsenal claimed their first national trophy, the FA Cup in 1930, and League Championships followed in 1930–31 and 1932–33.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Chapman also presided over off-pitch changes: white sleeves and shirt numbers were added to the kit; a Tube station was named after the club; and the first of two opulent Art Deco stands was completed, with some of the first floodlights in English football.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Suddenly, in the middle of the 1933–34 season, Chapman died of pneumonia.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] World War II meant the Football League was suspended for seven years.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] While Arsenal were paraded by the nation as a symbol of solidarity with war efforts, the war took a huge toll on the team as the club had had more players killed than any top flight club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Furthermore, debt from reconstructing an ambitious North Bank Stand redevelopment greatly bled Arsenal's resources.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Despite this period of turbulence and churn, Arsenal returned to win the league in the second post-war season of 1947–48.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This was Tom Whittaker's first season as manager, and meant the club equalled the champions of England record.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Whittaker, despite his disarming humble and modest disposition, was oft-referred to as the "brains" behind charismatic Chapman's legendary Arsenal side.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He gathered a successful and highly skilled Arsenal side in spite of greatly limited resources, with a fiery and expansive style that drove great fanfare at the time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] They won a third FA Cup in 1950, and then won a record-breaking seventh championship in 1952–53, making Arsenal the most successful team in English history at the time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal were not to win the League or the FA Cup for another 18 years.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The '53 Champions squad had aged, and the club failed to attract strong enough replacements.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Although Arsenal were competitive during these years, their fortunes had waned; the club spent most of the 1950s and 1960s in mid-table mediocrity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Even former England captain Billy Wright could not bring the club any success as manager, in a stint between 1962 and 1966.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal tentatively appointed club physiotherapist Bertie Mee as acting manager in 1966 to incredulity by fans, sportsmedia press.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With new assistant Don Howe and new players such as Bob McNab and George Graham, Mee led Arsenal to their first League Cup finals, in 1967–68 and 1968–69.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Next season saw a breakthrough, with Arsenal's first competitive European trophy, the 1969–70 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The season after, Arsenal achieved an even greater triumph with their first League and FA Cup double, and a new champions of England record.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This marked a premature high point of the decade; the Double-winning side was soon broken up and the rest of the decade was characterised by a series of near misses, with Arsenal finishing as FA Cup runners up in 1972, and First Division runners-up in 1972–73.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Former player Terry Neill succeeded Mee in 1976.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] At the age of 34, he became the youngest Arsenal manager to date.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] With new signings like Malcolm Macdonald and Pat Jennings, and a crop of talent in the side like Liam Brady and Frank Stapleton, the club reached a trio of FA Cup finals (1978 FA Cup, 1979 FA Cup and 1980 FA Cup), and lost the 1980 European Cup Winners' Cup Final on penalties.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club's only trophy during this time was the 1979 FA Cup, achieved with a last-minute 3–2 victory over Manchester United, in a final is widely regarded as a classic.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] One of Mee's double winners, George Graham, returned as manager in 1986, with Arsenal winning their first League Cup in 1987, Graham's first season in charge.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] New signings Nigel Winterburn, Lee Dixon and Steve Bould had joined the club by 1988 to complete the "famous Back Four", led by homegrown player Tony Adams.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The side immediately won the 1988 Football League Centenary Trophy, and followed it with the 1988–89 Football League title, snatched with a last-minute goal in the final game of the season against fellow title challengers Liverpool.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Graham's Arsenal won another title in 1990–91, losing only one match, won the FA Cup and League Cup double in 1993, the European Cup Winners' Cup in 1994, and also participated and was defeated in the 1994 European Super Cup final by European champions AC Milan.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Graham's reputation was tarnished when he was found to have taken kickbacks from agent Rune Hauge for signing certain players, and he was dismissed in February 1995.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] His replacement, Bruce Rioch, lasted for only one season, taking the side to the second European Cup Winners' Cup final in a row, lost against Real Zaragoza, but he left the club after a dispute with the board of directors.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club metamorphosed during the tenure of French manager Arsène Wenger, who was appointed in October 1996.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Attacking football, an overhaul of dietary and fitness practices, and elite scouting defined his reign.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Accumulating key players from Wenger's homeland, such as Patrick Vieira and Thierry Henry, Arsenal won a second League and Cup double in 1997–98 and a third in 2001–02.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In addition, the club reached the final of the 1999–2000 UEFA Cup, were victorious in the 2003 and 2005 FA Cup finals, and won the Premier League in 2003–04 without losing a single match, an achievement which earned the side the nickname "The Invincibles".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This feat came within a run of 49 league matches unbeaten from 7 May 2003 to 24 October 2004, a national record.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal finished in either first or second place in the league in eight of Wenger's first nine seasons at the club, although they never won the title in two consecutive seasons.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club had never progressed beyond the quarter-finals of the Champions League until 2005–06; in that season, they became the first club from London to reach the final in the competition's fifty-year history, but were beaten 2–1 by Barcelona.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In July 2006, they moved into the Emirates Stadium, after 93 years at Highbury.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal reached the finals of the 2007 and 2011 League Cups, losing 2–1 to Chelsea and Birmingham City respectively.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club had not gained a trophy since the 2005 FA Cup until, spearheaded by club record acquisition Mesut Özil, Arsenal beat Hull City in the 2014 FA Cup Final, coming back from a 2–0 deficit to win the match 3–2.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] A year later, Arsenal completed another victorious FA Cup campaign, and became the most successful club in the tournament's history by winning their 13th FA Cup in 2016–17.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] However, in that same season Arsenal finished fifth in the league, the first time they had finished outside the top four since before Wenger arrived in 1996.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In his 21st and final season, Arsenal under Arsène Wenger finished sixth and won the FA Community Shield.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Wenger departed Arsenal following the end of the season on 13 May 2018.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] After conducting an overhaul in the club's operating model to coincide with Wenger's departure, Spaniard Unai Emery was named as the club's new head coach on 23 May 2018.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He became the club's first ever 'head coach' and second manager from outside the United Kingdom.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In Emery's first season, Arsenal finished fifth in the Premier League and as runner-up in the Europa League.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 29 November 2019, Emery was dismissed as manager and former player and assistant first team coach Freddie Ljungberg was appointed as interim head coach.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 20 December 2019, Arsenal appointed former club captain Mikel Arteta as the new head coach.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal finished the 2019–20 season in eighth, their lowest finish since 1994–95, but beat Chelsea 2–1 to earn a record-extending 14th FA Cup win.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] After the season, Arteta's title was changed from head coach to manager.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 18 April 2021, Arsenal were announced as a founding club of the breakaway European competition The Super League; they withdrew from the competition two days later amid near-universal condemnation.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal finished the 2020–21 season in eighth place once again, not qualifying for a European competition for the first time in 26 years.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The season after (2021–22), Arteta had assembled the youngest outfit in the Premier League with an average starting age of 24 years and 308 days – more than a whole year younger than the next team.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] They finished in fifth in the Premier League that year, and qualified for next season's UEFA Europa League.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] By the 2022–23 season, Arsenal returned to the Champions League by coming second to Manchester City, setting a record for most time spent on top of the table without actually winning the league, ending on 84 points.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2023–24 season, Arsenal beat Manchester City to claim their 17th FA Community Shield, they finished second in the Premier League to Manchester City with an improved 89 points from their previous campaign.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2024–25 UEFA Champions League, they reached the semi-finals only to lose to PSG 3–1 on aggregate.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] For the third season in a row Arsenal finished second, this time behind Liverpool, amassing a points tally of 74 in the 2024–25 Premier League season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 19 May 2026, in the 2025–26 season, Arsenal secured its 14th league title and its first since the 2003–04 season with one game to spare, by virtue of AFC Bournemouth's 1–1 draw against Manchester City.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The title was Arsenal's first Premier League title under manager Mikel Arteta.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the same season, Arsenal reached the UEFA Champions League final for the second time in the club's history but lost to Paris Saint-Germain 4–3 on penalties after a 1–1 draw following extra time at the Puskás Aréna in Budapest.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Unveiled in 1888, Royal Arsenal's first crest featured three cannons viewed from above, pointing northwards, similar to the coat of arms of the Metropolitan Borough of Woolwich (nowadays transferred to the coat of arms of the Royal Borough of Greenwich).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] These can sometimes be mistaken for chimneys, but the presence of a carved lion's head and a cascabel on each are clear indicators that they are cannons.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] For the first time, the crest was rendered in colour, which varied slightly over the crest's lifespan, finally becoming red, gold and green.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Because of the numerous revisions of the crest, Arsenal were unable to copyright it.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Although the club had managed to register the crest as a trademark, and had fought (and eventually won) a long legal battle with a local street trader who sold "unofficial" Arsenal merchandise, Arsenal eventually sought a more comprehensive legal protection.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Therefore, in 2002 they introduced a new crest featuring more modern curved lines and a simplified style, which was copyrightable.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The cannon once again faces east, and the club's name is written in a sans-serif typeface above the cannon.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The new crest was criticised by some supporters; the Arsenal Independent Supporters' Association claimed that the club had ignored much of Arsenal's history and tradition with such a radical modern design, and that fans had not been properly consulted on the issue.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Until the 1960s, a badge was worn on the playing shirt only for high-profile matches such as FA Cup finals, usually in the form of a monogram of the club's initials in red on a white background.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The monogram theme was developed into an Art Deco-style badge on which the letters A and C framed a football rather than the letter F, the whole set within a hexagonal border.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This early example of a corporate logo, introduced as part of Herbert Chapman's rebranding of the club in the 1930s, was used not only on Cup Final shirts but as a design feature throughout Highbury Stadium, including above the main entrance and inlaid in the floors.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] From 1967, a white cannon was regularly worn on the shirts, until replaced by the club crest, sometimes with the addition of the nickname "The Gunners", in the 1990s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2011–12 season, Arsenal celebrated their 125th anniversary.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The celebrations included a modified version of the current crest worn on their jerseys for the season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The crest was all-white, surrounded by 15 oak leaves to the right and 15 laurel leaves to the left.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The oak leaves represent the 15 founding members of the club who met at the Royal Oak pub.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The 15 laurel leaves represent the design detail on the six pence pieces paid by the founding fathers to establish the club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The laurel leaves also represent strength.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] To complete the crest, 1886 and 2011 are shown on either sides of the motto "Forward" at the bottom of the crest.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Starting in the 2021–22 season, Adidas reintroduced the cannon-only crest on that season's away kit.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] It was the first time it had been seen on an Arsenal shirt since 1991.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] It would remain in use on the away kit in 2022–23 and in 2023–24 would be added to the third kit as well, before being used on all three kits in 2024–25 – marking the first time the crest would not be seen on an Arsenal kit since its introduction in 2002.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] White sleeves first appeared on the shirt in 1933.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Yellow shirt with blue trim and blue shorts are Arsenal's traditional away colours.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Since the 1990s, Blue has been prominently used for either the away or third kit.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] For much of Arsenal's history, their home colours have been bright red shirts with white sleeves and white shorts, though this has not always been the case.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The choice of red is in recognition of a charitable donation from Nottingham Forest, soon after Arsenal's foundation in 1886.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Two of Dial Square's founding members, Fred Beardsley and Morris Bates, were former Forest players who had moved to Woolwich for work.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] As they put together the first team in the area, no kit could be found, so Beardsley and Bates wrote home for help and received a set of kit and a ball.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The shirt was redcurrant, a dark shade of red, and was worn with white shorts and socks with blue and white hoops.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1933, Herbert Chapman, wanting his players to be more distinctly dressed, updated the kit, adding white sleeves and changing the shade to a brighter pillar box red.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Two possibilities have been suggested for the origin of the white sleeves.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] One story reports that Chapman noticed a supporter in the stands wearing a red sleeveless sweater over a white shirt; another was that he was inspired by a similar outfit worn by the cartoonist Tom Webster, with whom Chapman played golf.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Regardless of which story is true, the red-and-white shirts have come to define Arsenal, and the team have worn that combination ever since that time, aside from two seasons.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The first was 1966–67, when Arsenal wore all-red shirts; this proved unpopular, and the white sleeves returned the following season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The second was 2005–06, the last season that Arsenal played at Highbury, when the team wore commemorative redcurrant shirts similar to those worn in 1913, their first season in the stadium; the side reverted to their normal colours at the start of the next season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2008–09 season, Arsenal replaced the traditional all-white sleeves with red sleeves that bore a broad white stripe.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's home colours have been the inspiration for at least three other clubs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1909, Sparta Prague adopted a dark red kit like the one Arsenal wore at the time; in 1938, Hibernian adopted the design of the Arsenal shirt sleeves in their own green-and-white strip.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1941, Luis Robledo, an England-schooled founder of Santa Fe and a fan of Arsenal, selected the main colours for his newly created team.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1920, Sporting Clube de Braga's manager returned from a game at Highbury and changed his team's green kit to a duplicate of Arsenal's red-with-white-sleeves-and-shorts, giving rise to the team's nickname of *Os Arsenalistas*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] These teams still wear those designs to this day.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] For many years Arsenal's away colours were white or navy blue.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] However, in 1968 the FA banned navy shirts (they looked too similar to referees' black kit), so in the 1969–70 season Arsenal introduced an away kit of yellow shirts with blue shorts.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This kit was worn in the 1971 FA Cup Final when Arsenal beat Liverpool to secure the double for the first time in their history.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The yellow and blue strip became almost as famous as their iconic red-and-white home kit.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal reached the FA Cup final again the following year wearing the red-and-white home strip and were beaten by Leeds United.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal then competed in three consecutive FA Cup finals between 1978 and 1980 wearing their "lucky" yellow and blue strip, which remained the club's away strip until the release of a green and navy away kit in 1982–83.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The following season, Arsenal returned to the yellow and blue scheme, albeit with a darker shade of blue than before.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] When Nike took over from Adidas as Arsenal's kit provider in 1994, Arsenal's away colours were again changed to two-tone blue shirts and shorts.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Since the advent of the lucrative replica kit market, the away kits have been changed regularly, with Arsenal usually releasing both away and third choice kits.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] During this period the designs have been either all blue designs, or variations on the traditional yellow and blue, such as the metallic gold and navy strip used in the 2001–02 season, the yellow and dark grey used from 2005 to 2007, and the yellow and maroon of 2010 to 2013.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Until 2014, the away kit was changed every season, and the outgoing away kit became the third-choice kit if a new home kit was being introduced in the same year.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] After Puma began manufacturing Arsenal's kits in 2014, new home, away and third kits were released every season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2017–18 season, Puma released a new colour scheme for the away and third kits.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The away kit was a light blue, which faded to a darker blue near the bottom, while the third kit was black with red highlight.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Puma returned to the original colour scheme for the 2018–19 season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] From the 2019–20 season Arsenal's kits are manufactured by Adidas.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Before joining the Football League, Arsenal played briefly on Plumstead Common, then at the Manor Ground in Plumstead, then spent three years between 1890 and 1893 at the nearby Invicta Ground.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Upon joining the Football League in 1893, the club returned to the Manor Ground and installed stands and terracing, upgrading it from just a field.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal continued to play their home games there for the next twenty years (with two exceptions in the 1894–95 season), until the move to north London in 1913.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Widely referred to as Highbury, Arsenal Stadium was the club's home from September 1913 until May 2006.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The original stadium was designed by the renowned football architect Archibald Leitch, and had a design common to many football grounds in the UK at the time, with a single covered stand and three open-air banks of terracing.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The entire stadium was given a massive overhaul in the 1930s: new Art Deco West and East stands were constructed, opening in 1932 and 1936 respectively, and a roof was added to the North Bank terrace, which was bombed during the Second World War and not restored until 1954.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Highbury could hold more than 60,000 spectators at its peak, and had a capacity of 57,000 until the early 1990s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The Taylor Report and Premier League regulations obliged Arsenal to convert Highbury to an all-seater stadium in time for the 1993–94 season, thus reducing the capacity to 38,419 seated spectators.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] This capacity had to be reduced further during Champions League matches to accommodate additional advertising boards, so much so that for two seasons, from 1998 to 2000, Arsenal played Champions League home matches at Wembley, which could house more than 70,000 spectators.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Expansion of Highbury was restricted because the East Stand had been designated as a Grade II listed building and the other three stands were close to residential properties.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] These limitations prevented the club from maximising matchday revenue during the 1990s and first decade of the 21st century, putting them in danger of being left behind in the football boom of that time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] After considering various options, in 2000 Arsenal proposed building a new 60,361-capacity stadium at Ashburton Grove, since named the Emirates Stadium, about 500 metres south-west of Highbury.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The project was initially delayed by red tape and rising costs, and construction was completed in July 2006, in time for the start of the 2006–07 season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The stadium was named after its sponsors, the airline company Emirates, with whom the club signed the largest sponsorship deal in English football history, worth around £100 million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Some fans referred to the ground as Ashburton Grove, or the Grove, as they did not agree with corporate sponsorship of stadium names.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The stadium will be officially known as Emirates Stadium until at least 2028, and the airline will be the club's shirt sponsor until at least 2024.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] From the start of the 2010–11 season on, the stands of the stadium have been officially known as North Bank, East Stand, West Stand and Clock end.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The capacity of the Emirates now stands at 60,704.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's players train at the Shenley Training Centre in Hertfordshire, a purpose-built facility which opened in 1999.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Before that, the club used facilities on a nearby site owned by the University College of London Students' Union.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Until 1961 they had trained at Highbury.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's Academy under-18 teams play their home matches at Shenley, while the reserves play their games at Meadow Park, which is also the home of Boreham Wood.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Both the academy under-18 team and the reserves occasionally play their big games at the Emirates in front of a crowd reduced to only the lower west stand.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's fanbase are referred to as "Gooners" – the name derived from the club's nickname "The Gunners".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Virtually all home matches sell out; in 2007–08 Arsenal had the second-highest average League attendance for an English club (60,070, which was 99.5% of available capacity), and, as of 2015, the third-highest all-time average attendance.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 2025 Arsenal had the fifth-highest average attendance of Premier League clubs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Much of the Afro-Caribbean support comes from the neighbouring London Borough of Hackney and a large portion of the South Asian Arsenal supporters commute to the stadium from Wembley Park, North West of the capital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] There is also traditionally a large Irish community that followed Arsenal, with the surrounding Islington and particularly the nearby Archway area having a large community of residents with Irish heritage.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Like all major English football clubs, Arsenal have a number of domestic supporters' clubs, including the Arsenal Football Supporters' Club, which works closely with the club, and the Arsenal Independent Supporters' Association, which maintains a more independent line.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The Arsenal Supporters' Trust promotes greater participation in ownership of the club by fans.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] There have always been Arsenal supporters outside London, and since the advent of satellite television, a supporter's attachment to a football club has become less dependent on geography.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Consequently, Arsenal have a significant number of fans from beyond London and all over the world; in 2007, 24 UK, 37 Irish and 49 other overseas supporters' clubs were affiliated with the club.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] A 2011 report by SPORT+MARKT estimated Arsenal's global fanbase at 113 million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club is especially popular in Africa, owing to many of its players, past and present, such as those from the Wenger era, coming from Africa or being descendants from west Africa and the Caribbean.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] As a homage to this support, the 2024–25 alternative away kit used black, red and green to refer to the pan-African flag.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 2025 the club's social media activity was the fifth-highest among English football clubs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The team's anthem is "The Angel (North London Forever)" by Louis Dunford.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The song is typically played at Arsenal home games before a match.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In addition to the usual English football chants, Arsenal's supporters sing "One-Nil to the Arsenal" (to the tune of "Go West") and also regularly sing "Who's that team they call the Arsenal", "Good Old Arsenal" (to the tune of "Rule, Britannia!") and "We're the North Bank/Clock End Highbury".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The fans also chant "Boring, Boring Arsenal" in self-deprecating reference to Arsenal's reputation during the 1970s and 1980s as an overly defensive, cautious team.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's longest-running and deepest rivalry is with their nearest major neighbour, Tottenham Hotspur; matches between the two are referred to as the North London derby.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] There also exists a rivalry between Arsenal and Chelsea.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In addition, Arsenal and Manchester United developed a strong on-pitch rivalry in the late 1980s, which intensified in the early 2000s when both clubs were competing for the Premier League title.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club mascot is Gunnersaurus Rex, a smiling, seven-foot-tall green dinosaur, who first appeared at a home match against Manchester City in August 1994 (or 1993).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] He is based on a drawing by then-11-year-old Peter Lovell, whose design and another similar idea won a Junior Gunners contest; his official backstory is that he hatched from an egg found during renovations at Highbury.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] An online fundraiser was begun for Quy, and Mesut Özil offered to pay his salary himself as long as he remains with Arsenal.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In November 2020, in advance of COVID-19 regulations being relaxed to allow supporters to attend home games from 3 December, Arsenal announced that Gunnersaurus would return, to be played by a roster of people that could include Quy if he wished.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The largest shareholder on the Arsenal board is American sports tycoon Stan Kroenke.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Kroenke first launched a bid for the club in April 2007, and faced competition for shares from Red and White Securities, which acquired its first shares from David Dein in August 2007.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Red & White Securities was co-owned by Russian billionaire Alisher Usmanov and London-based Iranian financier Farhad Moshiri, though Usmanov bought Moshiri's stake in 2016.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Kroenke came close to the 30% takeover threshold in November 2009, when he increased his holding to 18,594 shares (29.9%).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In April 2011, Kroenke achieved a full takeover by purchasing the shareholdings of Nina Bracewell-Smith and Danny Fiszman, taking his shareholding to 62.89%.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In January 2018, Kroenke expanded his ownership by buying twenty-two more shares, taking his total ownership to 67.09%.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In August 2018, Kroenke bought out Usmanov for £550m.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Now owning more than 90% of the shares, he had the required stake to complete the buyout of the remaining shares and become the sole owner.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] There has been criticism of Arsenal's poor performance since Kroenke took over, which has been attributed to his ownership.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Ivan Gazidis was the club's Chief executive from 2009 to 2018.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's parent company, Arsenal Holdings plc, operates as an unlisted public limited company, whose ownership is considerably different from that of other football clubs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Only 62,219 shares in Arsenal have been issued, and they are not traded on a public exchange such as the FTSE or AIM; instead, they are traded relatively infrequently on the ICAP Securities and Derivatives Exchange, a specialist market.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 29 May 2017, a single share in Arsenal had a mid price of £18,000, which sets the club's market capitalisation value at approximately £1,119.9m.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Most football clubs are not listed on an exchange, which makes direct comparisons of their values difficult.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Consultants Brand Finance valued the club's brand and intangible assets at $703m in 2015, and consider Arsenal an AAA global brand.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Business magazine *Forbes* valued Arsenal as a whole at $2.238 billion (£1.69 billion) in 2018, ranked third in English football.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Research by the Henley Business School ranked Arsenal second in English football, modelling the club's value at £1.118 billion in 2015.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal's financial results for the 2019–20 season showed an after tax loss of £47.8m, due in part to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The Deloitte Football Money League is a publication that homogenises and compares clubs' annual revenue.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Deloitte put Arsenal's footballing revenue in 2019 at £392.7m (€445.6m), ranking Arsenal eleventh among world football clubs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal and Deloitte both listed the match day revenue generated in 2019 by the Emirates Stadium as €109.2m (£96.2m).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Partly due to their proximity to the Alexandra Palace transmitter, Arsenal have appeared in a number of media "firsts".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 22 January 1927, their match at Highbury against Sheffield United was the first English League match to be broadcast live on radio.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] A decade later, on 16 September 1937, an exhibition match between Arsenal's first team and the reserves was the first football match in the world to be televised live.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal also featured in the first edition of the BBC's *Match of the Day*, which screened highlights of their match against Liverpool at Anfield on 22 August 1964.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Sky's coverage of Arsenal's January 2010 match against Manchester United was the first live public broadcast of a sports event on 3D television.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] As one of the most successful teams in the country, Arsenal have often featured when football is depicted in the arts in Britain.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] They formed the backdrop to one of the earliest football-related novels, *The Arsenal Stadium Mystery* (1939), which was made into a film in the same year.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The story centres on a friendly match between Arsenal and an amateur side, one of whose players is poisoned while playing.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Many Arsenal players appeared as themselves in the film and manager George Allison was given a speaking part.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The book *Fever Pitch* by Nick Hornby was an autobiographical account of Hornby's life and relationship with football, and with Arsenal in particular.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Published in 1992, it formed part of the revival and rehabilitation of football in British society during the 1990s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The book was twice adapted for the cinema–the 1997 British film focuses on Arsenal's 1988–89 title win, and a 2005 American version features a fan of baseball's Boston Red Sox.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Arsenal have often been stereotyped as a defensive and "boring" side, especially during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 1997 film *The Full Monty* the principal characters move forward in a line and raise their hands, deliberately mimicking the Arsenal defence's offside trap, in an attempt to co-ordinate their striptease routine.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Fifteen years later, an almost identical scene was included in the 2012 Disney science-fiction film *John Carter* (director and co-writer Andrew Stanton, a notable overseas supporter of the club), along with other visual cues and oblique dialogue hints and references to the club throughout the film.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Another film reference to the club's defence comes in the film *Plunkett & Macleane*, in which two characters are named Dixon and Winterburn after Arsenal's long-serving full backs – the right-sided Lee Dixon and the left-sided Nigel Winterburn.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In August 2022, Amazon Prime Video released an eight-episode docuseries called *All or Nothing: Arsenal*.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 1985, Arsenal founded a community scheme, "Arsenal in the Community", which offered sporting, social inclusion, educational and charitable projects.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club support a number of charitable causes directly and in 1992 established The Arsenal Charitable Trust, which by 2006 had raised more than £2 million for local causes.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] An ex-professional and celebrity football team associated with the club also raised money by playing charity matches.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] The club launched the Arsenal for Everyone initiative in 2008 as an annual celebration of the diversity of the Arsenal family.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In the 2009–10 season Arsenal announced that they had raised a record breaking £818,897 for the Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In 2022, Arsenal and Adidas partnered up to launch the "No More Red" campaign to support the long-standing work being done by Arsenal in the Community to help keep young people safe from knife crime and youth violence.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] To promote the event, the club launched an exclusive all white kit that was not commercially available and only awarded to individuals who are making a positive difference in the community.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Save the Children has been Arsenal global charity partner since 2011 and have worked together in numerous projects to improve safety and well-being for vulnerable children in London and abroad.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 3 September 2016 The Arsenal Foundation has donated £1m to build football pitches for children in London, Indonesia, Iraq, Jordan and Somalia thanks to The Arsenal Foundation Legends Match against Milan Glorie at the Emirates Stadium.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] On 3 June 2018, Arsenal played Real Madrid in the Corazon Classic Match 2018 at the Bernabeu, where the proceeds went to Realtoo Real Madrid Foundation projects that are aimed at the most vulnerable children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] In addition there will be a return meeting on 8 September 2018 at the Emirates stadium where proceeds will go towards the Arsenal foundation.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] During 2007 in Pleiku, Vietnam, Arsenal partnered with the JMG Academy and the Hoang Anh Gia Lai Corporation to found a youth academy for the V.League 1 side Hoàng Anh Gia Lai, which saw a selection of Vietnam-based players train with Arsenal; the club ended their partnership with the club in 2017.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Additionally, the club formally partnered with a variety of clubs overseas including Virginia based Richmond Strikers and Cairo based Wadi Degla.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p01] Players with at least one first-team appearance for Arsenal.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal's tally of 14 League Championships is the third highest in English football, after Liverpool (20) and Manchester United (20), and they were the first club to reach a seventh and an eighth League Championship.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] As of June 2020, they are one of seven teams, the others being Manchester United, Blackburn Rovers, Chelsea, Manchester City, Leicester City and Liverpool, to have won the Premier League since its formation in 1992.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They hold the highest number of FA Cup trophies, with 14.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The club is one of only six clubs to have won the FA Cup twice in succession, in 2002 and 2003, and 2014 and 2015.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal have achieved three League and FA Cup "Doubles" (in 1971, 1998 and 2002), a feat only previously achieved by Manchester United (in 1994, 1996 and 1999).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They were the first side in English football to complete the FA Cup and League Cup double, in 1993.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal were also the first London club to reach the final of the UEFA Champions League, in 2006, losing the final 2–1 to Barcelona and they lost the Champions League final again, in 2026, 3-4 on penalties against Paris Saint-Germain, after a 1-1 draw.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal have one of the best top-flight records in history, having finished below fourteenth only seven times.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They have won the second most top flight league matches in English football, and have also accumulated the second most points, whether calculated by two points per win or by the contemporary points value.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They have been in the top flight for the most consecutive seasons (98 as of 2023–24).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal also have the highest average league finishing position for the 20th century, with an average league placement of 8.5.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal hold the record for the longest run of unbeaten League matches (49 between May 2003 and October 2004).
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] This included all 38 matches of their title-winning 2003–04 season, when Arsenal became only the second club to finish a top-flight campaign unbeaten, after Preston North End (who played only 22 matches) in 1888–89.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They also hold the record for the longest top flight win streak.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal set a Champions League record during the 2005–06 season by going ten matches without conceding a goal, beating the previous best of seven set by AC Milan.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] They went a record total stretch of 995 minutes without letting an opponent score; the streak ended in the final, when Samuel Eto'o scored a 76th-minute equaliser for Barcelona.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] David O'Leary holds the record for Arsenal appearances, having played 722 first-team matches between 1975 and 1993.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Fellow centre half and former captain Tony Adams comes second, having played 669 times.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The record for a goalkeeper is held by David Seaman, with 564 appearances.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Thierry Henry is the club's top goalscorer with 228 goals in all competitions between 1999 and 2012; he surpassed Ian Wright's total of 185 in October 2005.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Wright's record had stood since September 1997, when he overtook the longstanding total of 178 goals set by winger Cliff Bastin in 1939.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Henry also holds the club record for goals scored in the League, with 175, a record that had been held by Bastin until February 2006.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Declan Rice holds the Arsenal record signing price after a deal with West Ham United was completed in July 2023, for an initial £100 million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] This easily surpassed the former record of £72 million for Nicolas Pepe.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal's record home attendance is 73,707, for a UEFA Champions League match against Lens on 25 November 1998 at Wembley, where the club formerly played home European matches because of the limits on Highbury's capacity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The record attendance for an Arsenal match at Highbury is 73,295, for a 0–0 draw against Sunderland on 9 March 1935, while that at Emirates Stadium is 60,161, for a 2–2 draw with Manchester United on 3 November 2007.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal's first ever silverware was won as the Royal Arsenal in 1890.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The Kent Junior Cup, won by Royal Arsenal's reserves, was the club's first trophy, while the first team's first trophy came three weeks later when they won the Kent Senior Cup.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Their first national senior honour came in 1930, when they won the FA Cup.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The club enjoyed further success in the 1930s, winning another FA Cup and five Football League First Division titles.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal won their first league and cup double in the 1970–71 season and twice repeated the feat, in 1997–98 and 2001–02, as well as winning a cup double of the FA Cup and League Cup in 1992–93.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] The 2003–04 season was the only 38-match league season unbeaten in English football history.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] A special gold version of the Premier League trophy was commissioned and presented to the club the following season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] When the FA Cup was the only national football association competition available to Arsenal, the other football association competitions were County Cups, and they made up many of the matches the club played during a season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal's first first-team trophy was a County Cup, the inaugural Kent Senior Cup.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Arsenal became ineligible for the London Cups when the club turned professional in 1891, and rarely participated in County Cups after this.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] Due to the club's original location within the borders of both the London and Kent Football Associations, Arsenal competed in and won trophies organised by each.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] During Arsenal's history, the club has participated in and won a variety of pre-season and friendly honours.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] These include Arsenal's own pre-season competition the Emirates Cup, begun in 2007.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] During the wars, previous competitions were widely suspended and the club had to participate in wartime competitions.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/arsenal-f-c-p02] During WWII, Arsenal won several of these.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] The **Association of Commonwealth Universities** (**ACU**) is a charitable organisation that was established in 1913 which has over 400 member institutions in over 40 countries across the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] The ACU is the world's oldest international network of universities.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] Its mission is to promote and support excellence in higher education for the benefit of individuals and societies throughout the Commonwealth and beyond.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] The Association of Commonwealth Universities is governed by its member institutions through an elected council.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] As the ACU is a UK-registered charity, council members also act as its Trustees.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] The ACU Council comprises up to 23 members: 20 elected council members, up to two co-opted council members and, if the Honorary Treasurer is co-opted rather than elected, the Honorary Treasurer.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] In 1912, the University of London took the initiative to assemble 53 representatives of universities in London to hold a Congress of Universities of the Empire.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] They decided they needed a "bureau of information".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] Its affairs would be handled by a committee representing universities at home and abroad.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] In 1913 the office opened as the Universities Bureau of the British Empire.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] They incorporated under licence of the Board of Trade in 1919 and received a grant of £5000 to operate an office premises, with the understanding that the universities of the Empire would fund its maintenance.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] In 1948 the name was changed to Association of Universities of the British Commonwealth, and in 1963 it changed to its current name.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] Anastasios Christodoulou was the Secretary General of the Association of Commonwealth Universities from 1980 to 1996.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] In 1986, Queen Elizabeth II became patron of the Association of Commonwealth Universities.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] In 2019, Meghan, Duchess of Sussex became patron of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, a role which she held until February 2021.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] King Charles III was announced as the organisation's patron in May 2024.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] Currently 40 countries from the Commonwealth are represented in the Association.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/association-of-commonwealth-universities] Member universities are divided into full and associate categories, with the latter not holding voting rights.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She was born in Maidstone, Kent, where her father was a director of the Lead Wool Company, a tool company.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] Callaghan was educated at Maidstone Grammar School for Girls, then studied cookery at Battersea College of Domestic Science.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She would chair the Maidstone Labour Party and Fabian Society.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She joined the Labour Party while in her teens and met her future husband in the early 1930s at the Baptist church Sunday school where they both worked, then at the Labour Party, but they did not marry until 28 July 1938, her 23rd birthday.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] They honeymooned in Paris and Chamonix, and then returned to rent a house in Norwood.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She worked as a dietician at an antenatal clinic in Greenwich during the Second World War, a young mother herself.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] At the same time, she studied economics at a University of London extension course in Eltham, with future Labour Party leader Hugh Gaitskell as tutor.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She made a special study of malnutrition in children and its remedies.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] Her husband was elected a Member of Parliament for Cardiff in 1945.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] Audrey appeared publicly during his career, but generally remained private.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] One of her obituaries stated that she was engaged with her husband's jobs and was said to be instrumental in dissuading him from resigning after the 1967 devaluation of the pound.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] In 1958, Audrey was elected as the Labour member for Lewisham North for the London County Council.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She took a special interest in children's homes and the Children's Committee.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She was an alderman of the Greater London Council from 1964 and became chairman of Lewisham Council's children's committee, where she was also an alderman, when the GLC was abolished.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] In 1969, Callaghan became the chair of the board of governors of Great Ormond Street Hospital for Sick Children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She continued raising funds for the hospital for the next thirty years, most notably securing an extension of copyright on *Peter Pan* for the hospital by a Lords amendment moved by her husband.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] In 1987, when her husband created Baron Callaghan of Cardiff, she became Lady Callaghan.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She herself declined a damehood from Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] They retired to a farm in Ringmer, East Sussex, where she kept pigs and he kept cows and sheep, and grew barley.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] Along with her husband, she supported causes relating to the University College of Swansea, of which James Callaghan was president.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] During her eighties, Callaghan developed Alzheimer's disease.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] In July 2001, when her condition had deteriorated, she entered a care home in nearby Burgess Hill, West Sussex, where her husband visited her every day until her death on 15 March 2005, by which time they had been married for 66 years and together for well over 70.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] James Callaghan died on 26 March 2005, eleven days after Audrey's death, and the day before his 93rd birthday.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/audrey-callaghan] She had three children: Margaret Jay, Baroness Jay of Paddington, Julia and Michael.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital is the largest centre for child heart surgery in Britain and one of the largest centres for heart transplantation in the world.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 1962, it developed the first heart and lung bypass machine for children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] With children's book author Roald Dahl, it developed an improved shunt valve for children with hydrocephalus, and non-invasive (percutaneous) heart valve replacements.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Great Ormond Street performed the first UK clinical trials of the rubella vaccine, and the first bone marrow transplant and gene therapy for severe combined immunodeficiency.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital is the largest centre for research and postgraduate teaching in children's health in Europe.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Barrie donated the copyright to *Peter Pan* to the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The Hospital for Sick Children, Great Ormond Street was founded on 14 February 1852 after a long campaign by Dr Charles West, and was the first hospital in England to provide in-patient beds specifically for children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Despite opening with just 10 beds, it grew into one of the world's leading children's hospitals through the patronage of Queen Victoria, counting Charles Dickens, a personal friend of the Chief Physician Dr West, as one of its first fundraisers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The Nurses League was formed in February 1937.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Great Ormond Street Hospital was nationalised in 1948, becoming part of the National Health Service.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] During the early years of the NHS, private fundraising for the hospital was heavily restricted, though the hospital was permitted to continue to receive pre-existing legacies.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Audrey Callaghan, wife of James Callaghan (prime minister of the United Kingdom from 1976 to 1979), served the hospital as Chairman of the Board of Governors from 1968 to 1972 and then as Chairman of the Special Trustees from 1983 until her final retirement in 1990.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Diana, Princess of Wales, served as patron until her death in 1997.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The Charles West School of Nursing transferred from Great Ormond Street to London South Bank University in 1995.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2002 Great Ormond Street Hospital commenced a redevelopment programme which is budgeted at £343 million and the next phase of which was scheduled to be complete by the end of 2016.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In July 2012, Great Ormond Street Hospital was featured in the opening ceremony of the London Summer Olympics.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2017 Great Ormond Street Hospital was subject to international attention regarding the Charlie Gard treatment controversy.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital's archives are available for research under the terms of the Public Records Act 1958 and a catalogue is available on request.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Admission records from 1852 to 1914 have been made available online on the Historic Hospital Admission Records Project.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] St Christopher's Chapel is a chapel decorated in the Byzantine style and Grade II* listed building located in the Variety Club Building of the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Designed by Edward Middleton Barry (son of the architect Sir Charles Barry who designed the Houses of Parliament) and built in 1875, it is dedicated to the memory of Caroline Barry, Edward Middleton's sister-in-law.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] William Henry Barry, Caroline's widower, provided the £40,000 required to build the chapel and a stipend for the chaplain.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] It was built in "elaborate Franco-Italianate style".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] As the chapel exists to provide pastoral care to ill children and their families, many of its details refer to childhood.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The stained glass depicts the Nativity, the childhood of Christ and biblical scenes related to children.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The dome depicts a pelican pecking at her breast in order to feed her young with drops of her own blood, a traditional symbol of Christ's sacrifice for humanity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] When the old hospital was being demolished in the late 1980s, the chapel was moved to its present location via a "concrete raft" to prevent any damage en route.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The stained glass and furniture were temporarily removed for restoration and repair.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] It was reopened along with the new Variety Club Building on 14 February 1994 by Diana, Princess of Wales, then president of the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Barrie gave the copyright to his *Peter Pan* works to the hospital, with the request that the income from this source not be disclosed.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] This gave the institution control of the rights to these works, and entitled it to royalties from any performance or publication of the play and derivative works.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Innumerable performances of the play and its various adaptations have been staged, several theatrical and television adaptations have also been produced, and numerous editions of the novel have been published, all under licence from the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital's trustees further commissioned a sequel novel, *Peter Pan in Scarlet*, written by Geraldine McCaughrean and published in 2006.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] After the copyright first expired in the UK at the end of 1987 – 50 years after Barrie's death – the government's Copyright, Designs and Patents Act of 1988 granted the hospital a perpetual right to collect royalties for public performances and commercial publication of the work within the UK.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] This did not grant the hospital full copyright control over the work, however.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] When British copyright terms were later extended to the author's life plus *70* years by a European Union directive in 1996, Great Ormond Street revived its full copyright claim on the work.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] After the copyright expired again in 2007, the terms of the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act again applied.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital has relied on charitable support since it first opened.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] One of the main sources for this support is Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Whilst the NHS meets the day-to-day running costs of the hospital, the fundraising income allows Great Ormond Street Hospital to remain at the forefront of child healthcare.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The charity aims to raise over £50 million every year to complete the next two phases of redevelopment, as well as provide substantially more fundraising directly for research.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The charity also purchases up-to-date equipment, and provides accommodation for families and staff.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity was one of the charities that benefited from the national Jeans for Genes campaign, which encourages people across Britain to wear their jeans and make a donation to help children affected by genetic disorders.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] All Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity's proceeds from the campaign went to its research partner, the UCL Institute of Child Health.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] On 6 August 2009, Arsenal F.C. confirmed that Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity was to be their "charity of the season" for the 2009–10 season.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] They raised over £800,000 for a new lung function unit at the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Two charity singles have been released in aid of the hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 1987, "The Wishing Well", recorded by an ensemble line-up including Boy George, Peter Cox and Dollar amongst others became a top 30 hit.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2009, *The X Factor* finalists covered Michael Jackson's "You Are Not Alone" in aid of the charity, reaching No.1 in the UK Charts.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] On 30 March 2010, Channel 4 staged the first *Channel 4's Comedy Gala* at the O2 Arena in London, in aid of the charity.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The event has been repeated every year since, raising money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity each time.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2011, Daniel Boys recorded a charity single called "The World Is Something You Can Imagine".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] It was also released as with proceeds going to the Disney Appeal at Great Ormond Street Hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2018, celebrity supergroup The Celebs formed at Metropolis Studios to record an original Christmas song called "Rock With Rudolph", written and produced by Grahame and Jack Corbyn.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The song was in aid of Great Ormond Street Hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] It was released digitally through independent record label Saga Entertainment in November 2018.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The music video debuted exclusively with *The Sun* on 29 November 2018 and had its first TV showing on *Good Morning Britain* on 30 November 2018.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The song peaked at number two on the iTunes pop chart.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] At various times, Great Ormond Street has been involved in legal disputes in the United States, where the copyright term is based on date of publication, putting the 1911 novel in the public domain since the 1960s.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital asserted that the play, first published in 1928, was still under copyright in the US until the end of 2023.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Namely, that the service should provide an "exploratory" rather than "affirmative" approach to the child's health".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Some clinicians working on the new training materials and who did not resign are understood to have felt it important to affirm a patient’s gender identity and know that patients benefit from medication.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] This recommendation has also been criticised, due to ethical concerns around the nature of an "exploratory" approach.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Specifically, that it will result in biased clinicians carrying out conversion therapy.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] On 1 April 2024, despite opposition, the new Children and Young People's Gender Service began delivering for children and young people experiencing gender related distress.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In March 2024 NHS England confirmed children attending the regional centres will no longer receive puberty blockers and will be supported in line with the recommendations made by Dr Hilary Cass by "resulting in a holistic approach to care".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] One of the last acts of government in 2024 was to bring in an emergency ban on puberty blockers.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital's charity faced an investigation by the Information Commissioner's Office over potential breaches of data protection law in February 2017.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity was fined "£11,000 for sharing 910,283 records with other charities, sending on average 795,000 records per month to a wealth screening company and using email and birthdays to find out extra information about more than 311,000 supporters".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2024 Fundraisers working on behalf of Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity have found themselves embroiled in controversy due to allegations of employing "pressure-selling techniques".
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] These door-to-door fundraisers have been accused of coercing people into signing up for donations.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Great Ormond Street Hospital was involved in a scandal regarding the removal of live tissue and organs from children during surgery and onward sale to pharmaceutical companies without the knowledge of parents in 2001.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In January 2014, it was revealed that as a result of an accidental injection of glue into her brain, Maisha Najeeb brought a claim for compensation against the Great Ormond Street Hospital leading to a payment of up to £24million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In April 2018, it was revealed children were put at risk by being given potentially dangerous drugs.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In April 2019, following an inquiry into the death of Amy Allan, the coroner criticised the hospital for not providing a proper plan for the teenager's recovery after surgery.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2019 the Great Ormond Street mortuary manager made the senior leadership aware of staffing issues.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] "Since April 2019 GOSH mortuary has been very short staffed but somehow we have managed to keep our standards up, get through a HTA inspection and still give 100% care to our patients whilst having 50% staff.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The former Health Secretary, Jeremy Hunt, urged Great Ormond Street Hospital to examine a possible fundamental cultural problem amid claims it prioritizes reputation over patient care in March 2020.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In March 2020, the BBC conducted an investigation into the death of a child and revealed that at least six children had died of invasive aspergillosis at Great Ormond Street since 2016.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Several leaked emails from the head of Great Ormond Street Hospital, released in November 2020, suggested that the hospital had become accustomed to some "bad behaviours" and that more needed to be done to ensure staff feel safe.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In June 2021, the mother of a baby questioned why action was not taken sooner for her son who died at Great Ormond Street Hospital.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Great Ormond Street Hospital entered into an agreement with Sensyne, an AI company, in September 2021.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital received 1,428,571 shares in the company in exchange for patient data.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Sensyne has since been delisted from the London Stock Exchange leading to a loss to the hospital of around £2 million.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Following a lawsuit against Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Foundation Trust, a family received up to £7 million after the boy was left disabled, in July 2022.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In February 2023, the mother of a sick child with cancer was shocked after hearing Great Ormond Street hospital workers making jokes about his likely death.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In March 2023, it was revealed trainee dentist doctors at Great Ormond Street Hospital NHS Foundation Trust were going unsupervised.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In May 2023, newspapers highlighted the case of Ryan, left unattended in a lift by a Great Ormond Street hospital worker.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] His mother Catherine suffered a stress-induced seizure as she fell down the stairs and broke several bones after learning what happened to her son.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Ryan was found again after someone needed to use the trolley he was in, around 11 hours later.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] A spokesperson from the hospital said that there was a situation on the day of Ryan’s arrival and that they had half the number of staff that were due to be on duty.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Hospital cleaners have made allegations of institutional racism at Great Ormond Street Hospital in March 2023.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Hospital cleaners from minority ethnic groups say they were denied NHS contracts and paid less than white NHS employees.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] Each cleaner could receive between £80,000 and £190,000 if the claims are successful.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In August 2023 it was revealed a child began to experience lung complications with an invasive aspergillosis infection which led to his death.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2024 it was revealed that hundreds of children at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) have suffered life-altering injuries, including amputations, permanent deformities, and chronic pain, following their treatment by the consultant orthopedic surgeon Yaser Jabbar.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2013 a survey of more than 1,300 health units revealed Great Ormond Street Hospital had the second worst score in London and the 13th lowest score overall.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] The hospital that treats some of the country's most severely ill children and teenagers said it was surprised by the results of the first patient-led assessment of non-clinical issues.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] In 2023 a new patient-led assessment released by NHS Digital revealed Great Ormond Street Hospital was still ranked amongst the worst hospitals in UK with the 40th lowest score overall.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] As part of the assessment of food provision, assessors were asked questions regarding the choice of food offered, the availability of food 24 hours a day, meal times, and menu accessibility.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] A ward-level assessment of the food was also conducted, including an assessment of taste, texture, and serving temperature.
[src:great-ormond-street-hospital/great-ormond-street-hospital] in 2023 the patients-led assessment data released by NHS Digital also revealed Great Ormond Street Hospital was the third worst hospital in UK for cleanliness.
